body:
@scordio We discussed this in our team call today and were not sure about your use case.

Wouldn't the following be easy enough and not require any changes in JUnit?

```java
@ParameterizedTest
@EmptySource
void test(List<?> list) {
   ...
   legacyService.call(new ArrayList<>(list));
   ...
}
```

@marcphilipp Sorry, I forgot to provide the full background. My example goes together with the usage of `@NullSource`, something like:

```java
@ParameterizedTest
@NullSource
@MethodSource("emptyArrayList")
void test(ArrayList<?> list) {
   ...
   legacyService.call(list);
   ...
}
```

Your example would fail with an NPE at `new ArrayList<>(list)`.

`@NullAndEmptySource` would be my target if `@EmptySource` would support concrete types.

In the end, this is not a blocker and is mostly a cosmetic issue. We have a workaround but also the test can be rewritten in different ways to overcome the NPE and the unsupported concrete type, making it a bit more verbose.

Being a corner case, I totally understand if you'd rather not support it, but thought I'd ask for something that would improve the readability of the test.
